body:
Hi @white-hy 

When warping image `moving` to image `fixed`, the deformation field is in the space of the `fixed` image -- it tells you how to move the moving image to get to each grid location in the fixed image. For example, to get to location (123, 143) into the fixed space, it might tell you to grab (2.2, 1.3) voxels from the `moving image`. The reason this is a bit "backwards" is because moving pixels in this way enables us to *interpolate from the moving image* -- that is, we can get the "intensity value" at location (125.2, 144.3) from the moving image by bilinear interpolation, and move it to (123, 143).

But since this warp field is int he *fixed* space, warping *points* is a different story. If you have an exact point you want to move (e.g. at location (73.3, 54.1)), then this warp field only tells you how to move it from *fixed* to *moving* (since that's how it's set up. So, the `point_spatial_transformer` should be given the `fixed_image_landmarks`, not the moving image landmarks.

@zoujinger I am sorry for my late reply.  Maybe this is because the dimensions of the data are inconsistent. I can give you my code that I use to calculate TRE. 

```
moving_image_landmarks = np.loadtxt('./landmarksmoving_image_landmarks.txt')
fixed_image_landmarks = np.loadtxt( './landamrks/fixed_image_landmarks.txt')
dvf_Data = nib.load('./dvf/displacement.nii.gz')

fixed_image_landmarks = fixed_image_landmarks [np.newaxis, ...]
fixed_image_landmarks = tf.Variable(fixed_image_landmarks )

dvf_Data = dvf_Data[np.newaxis, ...]
dvf_Data = tf.Variable(dvf_Data)

# obtain moved_image_landmarks
moved_image_landmarks = point_spatial_transformer(fixed_image_landmarks , dvf_Data)
# moved_image_landmarks convert into ndarray
os.environ["CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES"] = '0'
sess = tf.Session()
init = tf.global_variables_initializer()
sess.run(init)
moved_image_landmarks = moved_image_landmarks .eval(session=sess)
moved_image_landmarks = np.squeeze(moved_image_landmarks )

difference = moved_image_landmarks - moving_image_landmarks 
# Landmarks include 300 points
for i in range(0,300,1):
        sum_difference += np.linalg.norm(difference[i])
# TRE
print(sum_difference/300)
```
Note that I used the `point_spatial_transformer `provided by  @adalca ï¼Œand You can find it up there. Also note that `moving_image_landmarks`, `fixed_image_landmarks`, and `dvf_Data` are all defined in the world coordinate system.
Thanks so much for your help!
